##AGE

plot_distribution <- function(dataset, feature) {
  # Computes and displays distribution of features with continuous values; plots their mean and median.
  
  hist(dataset[[feature]], breaks = "FD")
  
  abline(v = mean(dataset[[feature]]), col = "red", lwd = 2, lty = 2, label = "mean")
  abline(v = median(dataset[[feature]]), col = "orange", lwd = 2, lty = 2, label = "median")
  
  xlabel <- substitute(paste(feature))
  ylabel <- "Count"
  
  legend("topright", c("mean", "median"), lty = 2, col = c("red", "orange"), bty = "n")
  
  title(main = paste("Distribution of values in", feature), xlab = xlabel, ylab = ylabel)
}

#Overweight and Family history

library(ggplot2)

cross_plot <- function(dataset, lead_category, sup_category, order = NULL) {
  ggplot(data = dataset, aes(x = !!sym(lead_category), fill = !!sym(sup_category))) +
    geom_bar(position = "dodge") +
    labs(title = paste("Interaction between", lead_category, "and", sup_category),
         x = lead_category, y = "Count") +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 14, hjust = 0.5, face = "bold"),
          axis.title = element_text(size = 12, face = "bold"),
          axis.text = element_text(size = 10)) +
    scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Purples")
}

# Example usage:
cross_plot(data, "NObeyesdad", "family_history_with_overweight")

# Read in the dataset
data <- read.csv("C://Users//91999//Downloads//ObesityDataSet_raw_and_data_sinthetic.csv")
library(randomForest)
## randomForest 4.7-1.1
## Type rfNews() to see new features/changes/bug fixes.
## 
## Attaching package: 'randomForest'
## 
## The following object is masked from 'package:gridExtra':

##     combine

## The following object is masked from 'package:dplyr':
## 
##     combine

## 
##     margin
#na.omit(data)
# Convert NObeyesdad to a numeric format
data$NObeyesdad <- as.numeric(as.factor(data$NObeyesdad))

# Split the data into training and testing sets
set.seed(123) # for reproducibility
train_index <- createDataPartition(data$NObeyesdad, p = 0.7, list = FALSE, times = 1)
train <- data[train_index, ]
test <- data[-train_index, ]

# Train the bagged decision tree model
bag_model <- randomForest(NObeyesdad ~ ., data = train, ntree = 500, mtry = 4)

# Make predictions on the test set
predictions <- predict(bag_model, newdata = test)

# Evaluate the model performance
confusion_matrix <- table(predictions, test$NObeyesdad)
accuracy <- sum(diag(confusion_matrix)) / sum(confusion_matrix)
precision <- ifelse(colSums(confusion_matrix) > 0, diag(confusion_matrix) / colSums(confusion_matrix), 0)
recall <- ifelse(rowSums(confusion_matrix) > 0, diag(confusion_matrix) / rowSums(confusion_matrix), 0)
## Warning in diag(confusion_matrix)/rowSums(confusion_matrix): longer object
## length is not a multiple of shorter object length
f1_score <- ifelse(precision + recall > 0, 2 * precision * recall / (precision + recall), 0)

## object length
## Warning in 2 * precision * recall: longer object length is not a multiple of
## shorter object length
